In Hong Kong, the space for free speech has dramatically narrowed. Laws like the National Security Law are used to silence dissenting voices and redefine what is considered “dangerous speech.” Peaceful slogans or gatherings can now be classified as subversion or terrorism. Activists, journalists, and even students have been arrested or forced into exile. Courts increasingly favor state interpretation, and bail is routinely denied in political cases.

Surveillance has intensified — not just through street cameras or facial recognition, but via online platforms, message tracing, and even app data. Authorities may track communication patterns or identify contacts through seemingly minor digital traces.

These conditions create high personal risk for those voicing dissent. However, some methods remain harder to control. Offline communication, decentralized tools, and strong encryption can offer protection. Understanding concepts like anonymity networks, metadata minimization, device isolation, and secure storage methods opens doors to safer practices — especially under pressure or active targeting.

Protesters in Hong Kong used lasers to "blind" facial recognition cameras.
In response, authorities upgraded to infrared and heat-based recognition systems.